    "summary": "The Second Intermediate Period of Egypt (c. 1650–1550 BC) was an era of political fragmentation in which Egypt was divided among competing dynasties, most notably the [[event:1799|Hyksos]] Fifteenth Dynasty ruling the north from Avaris, an indigenous Seventeenth Dynasty at Thebes in the south, and a Nubian kingdom to the south. Egyptian sources describe this period as a time of chaos and humiliation, though modern scholarship recognizes a more complex picture of political coexistence and cultural exchange.\n\nThe Theban Seventeenth Dynasty gradually built up military strength and eventually launched a war of liberation against the Hyksos. The final campaigns were completed by Ahmose I around 1550 BC, who expelled the Hyksos from Egypt, reunified the country, and founded the Eighteenth Dynasty, inaugurating the [[event:60|New Kingdom]]. The trauma of Hyksos domination profoundly influenced New Kingdom imperial ideology and military policy.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Intermediate_Period_of_Egypt",
